WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.380
 So, up to now, we've mostly just talked about how forms work.

00:00:04.380 --> 00:00:06.680
 We've been talking about how forms work across

00:00:06.680 --> 00:00:08.360
 whatever programming language you're using

00:00:08.360 --> 00:00:09.260
 or framework you're using.

00:00:09.260 --> 00:00:12.460
 We've mostly talked about how the browsers treat forms,

00:00:12.460 --> 00:00:16.500
 how we generate HTML to make forms, how posts work,

00:00:16.500 --> 00:00:21.100
 how refresh works, how post redirect works, how CSRF works.

00:00:21.100 --> 00:00:23.340
 That's, other than subtle details,

00:00:23.340 --> 00:00:26.260
 those are topics that are true no matter what you do,

00:00:26.260 --> 00:00:28.540
 no matter what language you're writing in

00:00:28.540 --> 00:00:30.080
 or what framework that you're using.

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:31.800
 Now, we're gonna pivot a little bit

00:00:31.800 --> 00:00:35.900
 and talk about how Django helps you do all those things

00:00:35.900 --> 00:00:38.780
 that we just got done talking about doing.

00:00:38.780 --> 00:00:41.680
 So, if you look at this picture,

00:00:41.680 --> 00:00:43.780
 if you look at the picture, you see that like,

00:00:43.780 --> 00:00:46.320
 forms are kind of in the middle of this picture.

00:00:46.320 --> 00:00:48.480
 That's the final piece we're filling in.

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:50.920
 And forms are connected a lot of ways.

00:00:50.920 --> 00:00:52.560
 Forms can be connected to models.

00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:55.240
 They're used in the view and they're used in templates.

00:00:55.240 --> 00:00:59.720
 And so, they're a very powerful part and all the things

00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:01.280
 that we've been doing as abstractions,

00:01:01.280 --> 00:01:02.940
 where we write a little bit of code

00:01:02.940 --> 00:01:05.640
 and find lots of ways to reuse that code.

00:01:05.640 --> 00:01:07.920
 Or we write some code that extends an object

00:01:07.920 --> 00:01:09.200
 and then we add a little bit to it

00:01:09.200 --> 00:01:11.080
 and then we've got some very powerful object

00:01:11.080 --> 00:01:12.720
 when we're all said and done.

00:01:12.720 --> 00:01:15.360
 And so, that's what we're doing here in forms.

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:17.040
 And forms can be used in views, they can be used

00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:20.780
 in templates, and they can interact even with models.

00:01:20.780 --> 00:01:24.560
 And so, we're gonna talk a lot about forms.

00:01:24.560 --> 00:01:27.580
 There's a lot of like, just menial labor

00:01:27.580 --> 00:01:29.440
 that just work in in forms.

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:32.700
 And if you really had to build all the HTML by from scratch,

00:01:32.700 --> 00:01:35.320
 like I did in some of those earlier examples,

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:37.600
 it's just really painful.

00:01:37.600 --> 00:01:39.120
 And there's other problems too.

00:01:39.120 --> 00:01:40.480
 And that is that, you know,

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:42.480
 there's just a lot of repeating yourself.

00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:45.520
 We kind of want to use like object oriented techniques

00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:48.780
 and other techniques to not repeat ourselves.

00:01:48.780 --> 00:01:53.460
 And it's really easy to put a HTML for a crappy form,

00:01:53.460 --> 00:01:56.000
 but why wouldn't you want a beautiful form?

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:00.220
 And so, if you write the HTML and you write some CSS

00:02:00.220 --> 00:02:02.400
 and you do kind of crappy version of it,

00:02:02.400 --> 00:02:06.680
 then you have to fix it or hand it to a designer

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:09.580
 and then they have to go fix 100 pages.

00:02:09.580 --> 00:02:11.240
 There are things in Django,

00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:13.320
 crispy forms is something we'll talk about later,

00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:16.260
 that just like says, hey, I'm using forms in Django,

00:02:16.260 --> 00:02:18.080
 wait a sec, I want them to be pretty now.

00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:19.840
 And then you just make them pretty.

00:02:19.840 --> 00:02:21.440
 And if you want to change how they're pretty,

00:02:21.440 --> 00:02:24.380
 you can change how that works.

00:02:24.380 --> 00:02:26.500
 And then you change them all at the same time.

00:02:26.500 --> 00:02:28.800
 And so, not repeating yourself,

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:32.300
 being able to like lean on utility code.

00:02:32.300 --> 00:02:35.280
 Seems like why would we do this?

00:02:35.280 --> 00:02:36.640
 But in complex applications,

00:02:36.640 --> 00:02:38.320
 you just fall in love with this idea

00:02:38.320 --> 00:02:41.480
 that you don't have to repeat yourself.

00:02:41.480 --> 00:02:43.820
 And even though I've showed you some of the things

00:02:43.820 --> 00:02:48.080
 like post, redirect, refresh, CSRF, all that stuff,

00:02:48.080 --> 00:02:49.800
 it's even more complex than that,

00:02:49.800 --> 00:02:51.720
 especially when you start talking about

00:02:51.720 --> 00:02:54.000
 pulling data from the database

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:56.240
 and putting it in an edit form

00:02:56.240 --> 00:02:58.640
 and then checking to see if the data is valid.

00:02:58.640 --> 00:03:01.180
 If the data is not valid, send back an error form,

00:03:01.180 --> 00:03:02.840
 give a chance to resubmit it.

00:03:02.840 --> 00:03:05.780
 If they're successful, you do a post redirect

00:03:05.780 --> 00:03:08.320
 and then you send a message in the session.

00:03:08.320 --> 00:03:09.720
 We've done all that in really simple,

00:03:09.720 --> 00:03:11.640
 but if you really look at everything

00:03:11.640 --> 00:03:15.240
 that you need to look at, it's pretty complex.

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:18.240
 And so, we're not gonna do all this in this first lecture,

00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:21.500
 but this gives you a sense of the kinds of things

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:24.280
 that a create form, where you're gonna go like,

00:03:24.280 --> 00:03:26.600
 you know, new cat, and then you got some forms

00:03:26.600 --> 00:03:28.640
 to fill out, fields to fill out about the cat,

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:29.920
 and then you hit the save.

00:03:29.920 --> 00:03:31.280
 And so, if we just go through this,

00:03:31.280 --> 00:03:33.200
 these are the steps you need to do

00:03:33.200 --> 00:03:36.160
 to insert a cat in your cat database, right?

00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:39.300
 So, your browser initially goes and gets a get request,

00:03:39.300 --> 00:03:41.960
 and then you fill out the empty form

00:03:41.960 --> 00:03:44.000
 with a bunch of fill in the blank fields.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:46.680
 The user can almost cancel out of that and get out.

00:03:46.680 --> 00:03:49.460
 The user might enter some data and hit post.

00:03:49.460 --> 00:03:51.520
 Now, the problem is, what if you have some rules

00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:54.280
 about the data, such as this is required,

00:03:54.280 --> 00:03:57.440
 that has to be at least five characters, et cetera,

00:03:57.440 --> 00:04:00.760
 you have to then send a form back with that data

00:04:00.760 --> 00:04:03.160
 to let them fix it and resubmit it again.

00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:04.600
 Or if it's good, you go ahead

00:04:04.600 --> 00:04:06.540
 and store the data in the database,

00:04:06.540 --> 00:04:09.740
 but then we have to put some kind of a success message,

00:04:09.740 --> 00:04:11.540
 like in a session or something,

00:04:11.540 --> 00:04:13.800
 and then send a redirect out,

00:04:13.800 --> 00:04:15.720
 and then the browser immediately comes back

00:04:15.720 --> 00:04:18.480
 and gets the redirect URL, which pulls the message out,

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:21.040
 sends the page, and sends the success.

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:23.000
 And so we've done parts of this already, right?

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:24.720
 We've done parts of this already.

00:04:24.720 --> 00:04:27.120
 The big part we haven't done is kind of like

00:04:27.120 --> 00:04:30.440
 this middle part here where we're like validating the data

00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:32.560
 and have this error retry loop

00:04:32.560 --> 00:04:34.480
 that we put the user back in the loop

00:04:34.480 --> 00:04:36.920
 and give them another chance.

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:38.620
 Now, that's the create form.

00:04:38.620 --> 00:04:41.600
 The edit process where you're pulling in an existing cat

00:04:41.600 --> 00:04:44.460
 and you're gonna edit their fields is even more complex.

00:04:44.460 --> 00:04:46.480
 You know, you go load up a cat,

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:47.860
 but you might have an error page

00:04:47.860 --> 00:04:50.320
 'cause you don't get the, you don't get the,

00:04:50.320 --> 00:04:53.220
 they're looking for a cat that didn't exist in our database.

00:04:53.220 --> 00:04:54.600
 You send out the form with the old data.

00:04:54.600 --> 00:04:55.740
 They might leave.

00:04:55.740 --> 00:04:56.960
 They might edit it.

00:04:56.960 --> 00:04:57.860
 They might come back.

00:04:57.860 --> 00:05:00.360
 They might validate the data and get an error.

00:05:00.360 --> 00:05:01.840
 Then they have to fix the data.

00:05:01.840 --> 00:05:03.640
 They gotta go around here until,

00:05:03.640 --> 00:05:05.340
 okay, we got some valid data,

00:05:05.340 --> 00:05:07.400
 and then you store the data in the database,

00:05:07.400 --> 00:05:09.840
 send out a, put a message in a session,

00:05:09.840 --> 00:05:13.280
 send out a redirect to a success URL in that success URL.

00:05:13.280 --> 00:05:15.480
 You put out the message and say, yay.

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:19.920
 So that's complex, too, and we're gonna figure that out.

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:22.120
 Delete is not as simple as you might see,

00:05:22.120 --> 00:05:24.720
 and the problem with deleting things

00:05:24.720 --> 00:05:27.520
 is that you can't delete with a get request.

00:05:27.520 --> 00:05:29.120
 So usually you have to go navigate it

00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:30.800
 like you see a little delete button.

00:05:30.800 --> 00:05:32.960
 You click on it and you go to a delete page.

00:05:32.960 --> 00:05:35.560
 It's gonna load the data that you wanna delete

00:05:35.560 --> 00:05:37.160
 so you can build a confirmation page.

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:40.440
 Confirmation pages turn out to be really important

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:43.680
 'cause they're also a tricky way to convert a get to a post.

00:05:43.680 --> 00:05:45.140
 But if they're asking for the wrong data,

00:05:45.140 --> 00:05:46.780
 we have to send an error message.

00:05:46.780 --> 00:05:49.920
 Otherwise we send a confirmation form that says,

00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:52.080
 are you sure you wanna delete this?

00:05:52.080 --> 00:05:55.180
 That's both nice for the user to give a confirmation,

00:05:55.180 --> 00:05:57.760
 but it also then turns this into a form,

00:05:57.760 --> 00:05:59.280
 and of course they can leave with a cancel,

00:05:59.280 --> 00:06:02.060
 but if they click on yes, that turns into a post,

00:06:02.060 --> 00:06:04.360
 and it has the key, so the first thing it does

00:06:04.360 --> 00:06:07.700
 is it has to load the data again from the model,

00:06:07.700 --> 00:06:09.500
 and then if that data's not there,

00:06:09.500 --> 00:06:12.340
 they got the wrong key, then you send an error page out,

00:06:12.340 --> 00:06:14.240
 and if you got the right key

00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:16.600
 and the user has permission to delete the data,

00:06:16.600 --> 00:06:17.760
 then you go talk to the model

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:19.400
 and you delete the thing, right?

00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:22.380
 Then you put a congratulations on your deletion

00:06:22.380 --> 00:06:25.640
 in a session or something, then go with a redirect

00:06:25.640 --> 00:06:27.680
 'cause you can't respond with a 200.

00:06:27.680 --> 00:06:29.600
 You gotta respond with a 302,

00:06:29.600 --> 00:06:32.840
 and then the browser immediately does a get a success URL,

00:06:32.840 --> 00:06:34.160
 pulls the message out of session,

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:37.520
 makes a success page with the message.

00:06:37.520 --> 00:06:39.040
 Now we're gonna cover this a bunch of times.

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:41.540
 So you don't have to get this the first time,

00:06:41.540 --> 00:06:45.760
 but I just am telling you that forms are complex,

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:49.440
 and what's cool is Django form objects

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:52.500
 that we're gonna create act like glue.

00:06:52.500 --> 00:06:54.400
 They can generate the HTML,

00:06:54.400 --> 00:06:56.000
 they allow for a consistent look and feel,

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:58.600
 and they allow for you to change the look and feel.

00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:02.440
 When the post data comes back from the browser

00:07:02.440 --> 00:07:03.680
 in a form that it created,

00:07:03.680 --> 00:07:05.960
 then it puts it all in the right spot.

00:07:05.960 --> 00:07:08.440
 It validates the data based on a set of rules

00:07:08.440 --> 00:07:10.560
 that you say like this has to be this kind of a thing

00:07:10.560 --> 00:07:12.440
 and that kind of a thing or a date or a character

00:07:12.440 --> 00:07:14.080
 or an integer or a floating point.

00:07:14.080 --> 00:07:15.740
 Whatever it is the rules are,

00:07:15.740 --> 00:07:17.760
 that's all done for you in Django.

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:19.280
 And if something goes wrong,

00:07:19.280 --> 00:07:20.840
 then it hands you an error form

00:07:20.840 --> 00:07:22.760
 that you can send right back to the user.

00:07:22.760 --> 00:07:25.740
 And really greatly, and then of course,

00:07:25.740 --> 00:07:27.920
 once it's validated, it moves it into a model

00:07:27.920 --> 00:07:29.040
 and then actually can even

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:30.720
 to the database store automatically.

00:07:30.720 --> 00:07:33.440
 So the form is like this glue thing

00:07:33.440 --> 00:07:36.260
 that sort of talks to templates, it talks to browsers,

00:07:36.260 --> 00:07:39.440
 it reads data from browsers, it's like stuff in.

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:43.720
 And so in a way, the form is like the controller,

00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:48.160
 it's like the view, it just makes your views really succinct

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:51.460
 and you're gonna love it once you understand it.

00:07:51.460 --> 00:07:54.860
 So here is a simple form.

00:07:54.860 --> 00:07:59.460
 And so forms live in a file called forms.py, not surprisingly.

00:07:59.460 --> 00:08:01.560
 And basically just like them,

00:08:01.560 --> 00:08:03.260
 it looks a lot like the models file.

00:08:03.260 --> 00:08:05.240
 And so you're gonna see the one thing

00:08:05.240 --> 00:08:07.000
 that forms do differently is they can have

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:08.600
 these things called validators.

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:11.280
 Models have rules about max length, et cetera.

00:08:11.280 --> 00:08:13.320
 But there are even more complex validators

00:08:13.320 --> 00:08:16.320
 and you can even write code that you have your own functions

00:08:16.320 --> 00:08:18.240
 that when the form is coming in,

00:08:18.240 --> 00:08:19.600
 you're gonna look at this one field

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:22.440
 and you're gonna say like, oh, I wanted two uppercase

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:24.640
 characters followed by three lowercase characters.

00:08:24.640 --> 00:08:26.440
 Sorry, you didn't do what I said.

00:08:26.440 --> 00:08:27.680
 That's what's called a validator.

00:08:27.680 --> 00:08:29.880
 And that's when that error page goes back

00:08:29.880 --> 00:08:31.840
 and it says, hey, you're missing this stuff.

00:08:31.840 --> 00:08:34.240
 And we'll show you how the validator stuff works.

00:08:34.240 --> 00:08:36.480
 But basically you put in little lines

00:08:36.480 --> 00:08:39.000
 just like you did for the model.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:42.440
 And you're effectively defining a user interface

00:08:42.440 --> 00:08:44.680
 plus a bunch of logic behind it.

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:46.920
 Now the one thing I'm not doing in this particular section

00:08:46.920 --> 00:08:49.320
 we'll do soon is connecting this to a model.

00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:51.920
 So you could say, wait a sec, I'd like to make a form

00:08:51.920 --> 00:08:54.440
 and I will really mostly wanna inherit from a model.

00:08:54.440 --> 00:08:56.400
 You could do that, but that's not this one.

00:08:56.400 --> 00:08:59.000
 That's coming up in the whole next section,

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:00.540
 but it won't be long.

00:09:00.540 --> 00:09:03.920
 So the form object, right?

00:09:03.920 --> 00:09:06.360
 We're gonna, so here's this form we just made.

00:09:06.360 --> 00:09:07.800
 It's got three fields in it.

00:09:07.800 --> 00:09:09.640
 And this is a real simple view.

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:10.920
 It's not useful.

00:09:10.920 --> 00:09:14.160
 It just kinda shows you one of the things you can do.

00:09:14.160 --> 00:09:15.960
 So make a basic form.

00:09:15.960 --> 00:09:19.040
 When the basic form is defined as having these three fields

00:09:19.040 --> 00:09:22.640
 and then you say form and then call the method as table.

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:24.980
 And so what this produces, it's just a dump.

00:09:24.980 --> 00:09:28.000
 There's nothing, the UI of this looks really ugly.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.440
 But basically it generates all this HTML for you.

00:09:30.440 --> 00:09:31.680
 All this HTML.

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:34.520
 Input tags and it's, we told it to do it as table.

00:09:34.520 --> 00:09:36.160
 That's necessarily not necessarily the prettiest way

00:09:36.160 --> 00:09:39.520
 to do it, but all that HTML is generated

00:09:39.520 --> 00:09:40.840
 from the form utility.

00:09:40.840 --> 00:09:42.720
 So it can send it out as a list.

00:09:42.720 --> 00:09:45.120
 You can send it out as paragraphs, et cetera, et cetera,

00:09:45.120 --> 00:09:45.960
 et cetera.

00:09:45.960 --> 00:09:49.640
 And so this is just to show you kinda the dump.

00:09:49.640 --> 00:09:51.920
 If you go to this URL, do a view source on it.

00:09:51.920 --> 00:09:53.760
 So you see this stuff in here.

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:56.060
 So that you define a form object

00:09:56.060 --> 00:09:58.520
 and one of the things you can do is make me HTML.

00:09:58.520 --> 00:10:02.020
 And this is not a good example, we'll come up in a bit

00:10:02.020 --> 00:10:03.640
 with a better example.

00:10:03.640 --> 00:10:06.720
 The better example, of course, is to use it in a template.

00:10:06.720 --> 00:10:10.000
 And so here is a template with a simple form in it.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:11.680
 We got a form, it's a post.

00:10:11.680 --> 00:10:13.040
 We got some submit stuff.

00:10:13.040 --> 00:10:17.400
 We got ourselves a cancel, you know, button that we put in.

00:10:17.400 --> 00:10:19.240
 And we got a CSRF token.

00:10:19.240 --> 00:10:21.320
 And we're gonna use that form as table.

00:10:21.320 --> 00:10:23.140
 And we're gonna surround it by a table tag

00:10:23.140 --> 00:10:25.100
 so that it looks a lot prettier.

00:10:25.100 --> 00:10:28.140
 And so this is a far more typical way of doing it.

00:10:28.140 --> 00:10:30.560
 That first one was just to dump it.

00:10:30.560 --> 00:10:33.560
 And so this, when you do this and you give it,

00:10:33.560 --> 00:10:36.720
 you sort of make the form in a get request.

00:10:36.720 --> 00:10:39.880
 You make the form and you pass it into the context.

00:10:39.880 --> 00:10:43.580
 If you remember, form.as table, that's a very, come back.

00:10:43.580 --> 00:10:46.400
 Too far, too far.

00:10:46.400 --> 00:10:49.600
 Form.as table came from the context,

00:10:49.600 --> 00:10:51.460
 came from the passed in variable.

00:10:51.460 --> 00:10:53.680
 And that is right here and right here.

00:10:53.680 --> 00:10:55.800
 And so we make the form object,

00:10:55.800 --> 00:10:57.560
 which has all the fields in it.

00:10:57.560 --> 00:11:01.000
 And then we pass it into our view, our template.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:02.540
 And it renders that.

00:11:02.540 --> 00:11:05.640
 And so then, this is what it looks like much prettier.

00:11:05.640 --> 00:11:07.320
 And if you do a view source of that,

00:11:07.320 --> 00:11:09.480
 if you go to this form create,

00:11:09.480 --> 00:11:11.120
 and you do a view source on that,

00:11:11.120 --> 00:11:14.880
 you'll see it's all that same table stuff.

00:11:14.880 --> 00:11:17.520
 You know, it's the same table stuff that we had before.

00:11:17.520 --> 00:11:18.880
 It's just now wrapped in some stuff

00:11:18.880 --> 00:11:20.040
 to make it look a little prettier.

00:11:20.040 --> 00:11:22.140
 We put a submit button, it's got a form tag.

00:11:22.140 --> 00:11:23.840
 And then you can actually hit the submit button

00:11:23.840 --> 00:11:25.560
 and something actually happens.

00:11:25.560 --> 00:11:27.580
 So this is by far the more typical way

00:11:27.580 --> 00:11:29.740
 of using the form in a template.

00:11:29.740 --> 00:11:32.800
 So I talked about the create form,

00:11:32.800 --> 00:11:35.240
 the update form, and the delete form.

00:11:35.240 --> 00:11:38.780
 This is kind of an example of how forms can be used.

00:11:38.780 --> 00:11:42.320
 Now, I'm not actually talking on the model yet.

00:11:42.320 --> 00:11:44.080
 We'll do that in a bit.

00:11:44.080 --> 00:11:46.680
 So I'm just gonna pretend that we have some old data.

00:11:46.680 --> 00:11:49.240
 And so this normally would come from the model,

00:11:49.240 --> 00:11:51.760
 this old data, title, mileage, purchase date.

00:11:51.760 --> 00:11:53.600
 That would come from the model normally.

00:11:53.600 --> 00:11:56.120
 But for now, we're just gonna like make it up.

00:11:56.120 --> 00:11:58.340
 And so then you basically start a form

00:11:58.340 --> 00:12:01.360
 and you pass this old data in as the constructor.

00:12:01.360 --> 00:12:03.520
 That's a constructor for a basic form

00:12:03.520 --> 00:12:06.840
 from the basic form class, pass in old data,

00:12:06.840 --> 00:12:11.760
 and give me back an object of type basic form.

00:12:11.760 --> 00:12:13.840
 And I'm gonna have it in the variable form,

00:12:13.840 --> 00:12:16.480
 and then I'm gonna pass it into context.

00:12:16.480 --> 00:12:18.840
 Now you'll notice I'm using the exact same template,

00:12:18.840 --> 00:12:20.960
 the one I showed you before,

00:12:20.960 --> 00:12:23.720
 because that form as table understands

00:12:23.720 --> 00:12:25.800
 that sometimes there's data in these fields,

00:12:25.800 --> 00:12:27.680
 and it properly puts the data in.

00:12:27.680 --> 00:12:29.440
 It properly escapes the data.

00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:31.340
 It understands that this is a number.

00:12:31.340 --> 00:12:33.400
 It understands that this is a date.

00:12:33.400 --> 00:12:35.880
 It's got all that stuff all figured out, right?

00:12:35.880 --> 00:12:37.120
 And so this is how it works,

00:12:37.120 --> 00:12:39.680
 is you just somehow get your hands on

00:12:39.680 --> 00:12:41.400
 key value pairs of the old data,

00:12:41.400 --> 00:12:43.200
 you pass it into the constructor,

00:12:43.200 --> 00:12:45.440
 and now you render the form,

00:12:45.440 --> 00:12:47.160
 and the forms library takes care

00:12:47.160 --> 00:12:49.040
 of putting in all that old data.

00:12:49.900 --> 00:12:51.360
 Believe you me, you're probably glad

00:12:51.360 --> 00:12:53.960
 I'm not showing you how to do HTML and code

00:12:53.960 --> 00:12:55.920
 and all these things, and when you do encode,

00:12:55.920 --> 00:12:57.040
 but this is a little different

00:12:57.040 --> 00:12:58.840
 'cause it's inside of an attribute.

00:12:58.840 --> 00:12:59.680
 You don't wanna know that

00:12:59.680 --> 00:13:02.320
 because you just are gonna use form as table,

00:13:02.320 --> 00:13:04.320
 and it's got all the rules figured out.

